    <div class="article-body">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>Provenance — Lake Tahoe to the Pacific Northwest</h2>
        <p>
          The car is originally from South Shore Lake Tahoe, California. It eventually made its way north to
          Sequim, Washington, where it's believed to have received a respray in its original Poppy Red and an
          interior refresh — possibly not entirely correctly — under an earlier owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Carl, a Sequim-based enthusiast who'd known the car for decades, bought it in 2013. Working the
          case and chassis stampings, he determined the engine case was stamped within about two weeks of
          the chassis — close enough to be correct for the period, though it can't be certified as
          numbers-matching. Carl rebuilt the engine, including a big-bore upgrade to nearly 1500cc, and
          refreshed the interior correctly this time.
        </p>
        <div class="callout auth">
          <b>On the record:</b> all-original sheet metal — this car has never had bodywork, a rarity for a
          60-year-old convertible. Engine case stamped within roughly two weeks of the chassis date; correct
          for the period, not certifiably matching.
        </div>
        <p>
          Rusty bought the car from Carl in 2021. It was transported by trailer and garaged that same day,
          and has lived in a dry, insulated, temperature-controlled garage since — engine at well under 50
          miles since Carl's rebuild at the time of purchase. The whole car has been reconditioned to the
          point that it runs and looks nearly new.
        </p>

        <div class="callout"><b>Fun fact:</b> the Beetle and the 356 share more than a driveway. Ferdinand Porsche's design firm developed the original Beetle in the 1930s for the German government, and the early 356 — particularly the 356/2 — borrowed several of its components directly from the Beetle: the air-cooled, rear-mounted engine, rear-wheel drive, and independent rear suspension. The 356's engine started as a modified version of the Beetle's, with more displacement and better carburetion, before Porsche's own engineering took it somewhere entirely its own.</div>

        <h2>The car today</h2>
        <p>
          Top down, Poppy Red, and out at shows — a driver, not a trailer queen, even with the mileage kept
          low.
        </p>

